"""
MKT Context Commentary — Zephaniah chapters 1–3 (all 53 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-zephaniah-1-3.py

Zephaniah prophesied during the reign of Josiah (640-609 BCE), likely before
the 621 BCE reform (the book's description of widespread idolatry matches the
pre-reform period). He is identified as great-great-grandson of Hezekiah —
possibly the king, making him of royal blood. He develops the Day of the LORD
concept more thoroughly than any other prophet (cf. Amos 5:18-20; Joel 1-2).
The Latin Dies Irae hymn is drawn from Zeph 1:15-16.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ZEPHANIAH = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Zephaniah's genealogy is uniquely elaborate — four generations are listed, tracing his lineage back to Hezekiah. If this is King Hezekiah (715-687 BCE), then Zephaniah is of Davidic royal blood, the only writing prophet so identified. This would make him a social peer of the royal court he addresses, giving his oracles against the princes and royal officials (1:8) a distinctive personal authority. The date in Josiah's reign (640-609 BCE) places him early in the reform period — the idolatry described in ch. 1 matches the pre-621 situation before the Book of the Law was found in the temple (2 Kgs 22).</p>",
    "2": "<p>'I will utterly sweep away everything from the face of the earth, declares YHWH.' The opening oracle immediately deploys creation-reversal language. The verb <em>asof asof</em> (I will utterly sweep away — the intensifying infinitive absolute) announces comprehensive judgment. The list in vv. 2-3 reverses Genesis 1 in reverse order: humans, animals, birds, fish — creation undone in a de-creation sweep. The scope is cosmic before it narrows to the specific: Judah, Jerusalem, the ruling class.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'I will sweep away humans and animals; I will sweep away the birds of the heavens and the fish of the sea, and the rubble with the wicked. I will cut off humanity from the face of the earth, declares YHWH.' The de-creation sequence: Genesis 1 created fish, birds, animals, humans; here the judgment reverses the sequence. The rubble (<em>hamikashelot</em>) swept away with the wicked may refer to idols (obstacles/stumbling blocks) or to the accumulated wreckage of Judah's religious corruption. The phrase 'face of the earth' (<em>penei ha'adamah</em>) recalls Adam's formation from the <em>adamah</em> (ground) — the creature made from dust is swept from the dust.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'I will stretch out my hand against Judah and against all the inhabitants of Jerusalem; and I will cut off from this place the remnant of Baal and the name of the idolatrous priests along with the priests.' After the cosmic announcement, the oracle narrows to Judah and Jerusalem. The stretched hand (<em>natiti yadi</em>) is the gesture of the divine warrior (Exod 7:5; 14:16; Deut 4:34). The idolatrous priests (<em>kemarim</em>) are a specific term for Baalist priests who burned incense on rooftops (2 Kgs 23:5 uses the same word for the priests Josiah dismissed). Zephaniah's oracle anticipates the Josianic reform.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Those who bow down on the rooftops to the host of heaven, those who bow down and swear to YHWH and yet swear by Milcom.' Roof-top astral worship — stars, moon, and planets worshiped from the highest vantage point — was prevalent under Manasseh (2 Kgs 21:3-5; 23:4-5). Milcom (or Molech) was the Ammonite deity. The double allegiance — swearing both by YHWH and by Milcom — is the syncretism Zephaniah condemns: not pure Baalism but the blending of YHWH worship with neighboring cults, which the Deuteronomic law explicitly forbids (Deut 17:3; 4:19).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Those who have turned back from following YHWH, who do not seek YHWH or inquire of him.' The third category: not active idolaters but passive apostates — those who have simply stopped following YHWH, no longer seeking him through prayer, sacrifice, or oracle inquiry (<em>darash</em>). This indifference is as condemned as active Baal worship; the covenant requires active loyalty, not merely the absence of competing allegiances. The phrase 'turned back from following' (<em>hannisogim me'acharei YHWH</em>) is the covenant-loyalty language of Joshua and Deuteronomy applied to the abandonment of religious practice.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Be silent before the Lord YHWH! For the day of YHWH is near; YHWH has prepared a sacrifice and consecrated his guests.' The command for silence (<em>has</em>) before YHWH is the summons to awe in a divine court (cf. Hab 2:20; Zech 2:13; Amos 6:10). The Day of YHWH as a sacrifice (<em>zevach</em>) is a striking metaphor: YHWH himself as the priest slaughtering the sacrificial victim — the victim being Judah's ruling class. The 'consecrated guests' (<em>mequdashaiv</em>) invited to this grim feast are likely Judah's enemies (Assyria, or later Babylon) summoned by YHWH to consume the sacrifice.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'And on the day of YHWH's sacrifice — I will punish the officials and the king's sons and all who array themselves in foreign attire.' The first specific target: the ruling class. The princes (<em>sarim</em>) and the king's sons (<em>benei hamelech</em>) — the courtiers and princes who had adopted Assyrian fashions (foreign attire as a symbol of cultural capitulation to the empire). The adoption of Assyrian dress was part of the broader cultural syncretism; wearing Assyrian garments in the court signaled loyalty to Assyrian imperial culture over covenant identity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'On that day I will punish everyone who leaps over the threshold, and those who fill their master's house with violence and fraud.' The leaping over the threshold (<em>medaleggim al hamiftan</em>) is obscure — it may refer to the Philistine practice of not stepping on the threshold of Dagon's temple (1 Sam 5:5), which some Israelites had adopted supstitiously; or it may refer to aggressive entry into others' homes for the purpose of plunder. Either way, the accompanying charge of filling the master's house with violence and fraud places this in the context of exploitative commerce and property seizure.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'On that day, declares YHWH, a cry will be heard from the Fish Gate, a wail from the Second Quarter, a loud crash from the hills.' The Fish Gate was on Jerusalem's north wall (Neh 3:3) — the direction from which enemy armies typically approached. The Second Quarter (Mishneh) was a newer residential district that Huldah the prophetess inhabited (2 Kgs 22:14). The topographic specificity — Fish Gate, Second Quarter, hills — makes this an urban oracle about the advance of destruction through Jerusalem's specific neighborhoods.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Wail, O inhabitants of the Mortar! For all the traders are no more; all who weigh out silver are cut off.' The Mortar (<em>hamachtesh</em>) was apparently a commercial district in Jerusalem — the name suggests a bowl-shaped depression, possibly the Tyropoeon Valley between the two hills, where merchants gathered. The traders (<em>am kena'an</em>, literally 'people of Canaan') — the term for merchants, since Canaanites were associated with commerce. The commercial district is specifically targeted because its commerce is infected with the fraudulent weights condemned throughout the prophets.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'At that time I will search Jerusalem with lamps, and I will punish the men who are complacent, those who say in their hearts, YHWH will not do good, nor will he do ill.' The divine search of Jerusalem with lamps — a thorough, inescapable investigation. The specific target is complacency (<em>haqqofe'im al shemarehim</em>, those thickening/congealing on their dregs — wine that sits too long becomes thick and syrupy, losing its character). The theology of the complacent: YHWH is functionally inactive — he does neither good nor evil, neither rewards nor punishes. This practical deism — not atheism but divine passivity — is the specific spiritual disease Zephaniah diagnoses.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Their goods shall be plundered, and their houses laid waste. Though they build houses, they shall not inhabit them; though they plant vineyards, they shall not drink wine from them.' The covenant curses of Deut 28:30 ('you shall build a house, but you shall not dwell in it; you shall plant a vineyard, but you shall not enjoy its fruit') applied to the complacent class. The irony of interrupted investment: the luxury houses built by the wealthy through exploitation will be stripped; the vineyards planted with the proceeds of fraud will yield wine for someone else.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'The great day of YHWH is near, near and hastening fast; the sound of the day of YHWH is bitter; the mighty man cries aloud there.' The great Day of YHWH (<em>yom YHWH hagadol</em>) — Zephaniah develops this concept most thoroughly of all the prophets. 'Near and hastening fast' (<em>qarov mehera me'od</em>) — the temporal urgency is doubled. Even the mighty man (<em>gibbor</em>) — the warrior, the hero — cries aloud in terror. Military prowess provides no refuge from divine judgment.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'A day of wrath is that day, a day of distress and anguish, a day of ruin and devastation, a day of darkness and gloom, a day of clouds and thick darkness.' The famous catalog of the Day of YHWH: seven pairs of negative characteristics. This verse and v. 16 provided the core vocabulary for the medieval Latin hymn <em>Dies Irae</em> (Day of Wrath), used in the Requiem Mass for centuries. The darkness imagery draws on the Exodus plague of darkness (Exod 10:21-23) and Amos 5:18-20 (the Day of YHWH as darkness not light). The combination of meteorological (clouds, gloom) and emotional (distress, anguish) terms makes the Day simultaneously cosmic and deeply personal.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'A day of trumpet blast and battle cry against the fortified cities and against the lofty battlements.' The trumpet (<em>shofar</em>) and battle cry (<em>teruah</em>) against fortified cities — the siege warfare announcement. The fortified cities and lofty battlements (literally 'corner towers') represent the ultimate human defensive engineering — Jerusalem's walls and towers that the city's inhabitants trusted for protection. The Day of YHWH exposes the inadequacy of even the most advanced defensive architecture.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I will bring distress on mankind, so that they shall walk like the blind, because they have sinned against YHWH; their blood shall be poured out like dust, and their flesh like dung.' The blindness (<em>vehilachti la'anashim vehalchu ka'ivrim</em>) — judgment as disorientation, loss of capacity to navigate. Walking like the blind is the covenant curse of Deut 28:29 ('you shall grope at noonday, as the blind grope in darkness'). Blood like dust and flesh like dung — extreme debasement, the reversal of the dignity of human embodiment. This language is deliberately shocking.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Neither their silver nor their gold shall be able to deliver them on the day of the wrath of YHWH. In the fire of his jealousy, all the earth shall be consumed; for a full and sudden end he will make of all the inhabitants of the earth.' The final verdict: wealth is no refuge. Silver and gold (<em>kasefam uzehavam</em>) cannot purchase exemption from divine judgment. The 'fire of his jealousy' (<em>be'esh qin'ato</em>) — divine jealousy as fire consuming — connects to the covenant term <em>El qanna</em> (jealous God) of the Decalogue (Exod 20:5) and Nahum 1:2. The whole earth consumed: the oracle that began with cosmic scope (vv. 2-3) ends with cosmic scope — the Day is not only for Judah.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>'Gather together, yes, gather, O shameless nation, before the decree takes effect — before the day passes away like chaff — before there comes upon you the burning anger of YHWH, before there comes upon you the day of the anger of YHWH.' The urgent summons to assembly before the judgment falls. The nation addressed (<em>goy lo nichsaf</em>, 'nation not yearned for' or 'shameless nation') is Judah. The twice-repeated urgency ('gather, yes, gather') and the triple 'before' clauses create mounting temporal pressure: the decree is already issued; the day is already in motion; repentance must happen before the window closes.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Before the decree takes effect — before the day passes away like chaff — before there comes upon you the burning anger of YHWH, before there comes upon you the day of the anger of YHWH.' The second verse continues the triple urgency of v. 1, intensifying the temporal compression. The chaff image (<em>kehavor yom ya'avor</em>) — the day passing like chaff in the wind — is vivid and brief. Chaff is the symbol of transience and judgment throughout the psalms and wisdom literature (Ps 1:4; Isa 17:13; 29:5). The window for repentance is as brief as chaff before the wind.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Seek YHWH, all you humble of the land, who do his just commands; seek righteousness; seek humility; perhaps you may be hidden on the day of the anger of YHWH.' The positive address embedded within the judgment oracle: the <em>anavei ha'aretz</em> (humble of the land) who do justice are offered the possibility of shelter on the Day. The threefold 'seek' (<em>baqshu YHWH... baqshu tzedek... baqshu anavah</em>) creates a penitential program. The crucial word is <em>ulay</em> (perhaps) — no guarantee is offered, only possibility. Authentic penitence cannot be transactional; the humble of the land seek YHWH without a contractual assurance of escape.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'For Gaza shall be deserted, and Ashkelon shall become a desolation; Ashdod's people shall be driven out at noon, and Ekron shall be uprooted.' The oracles against the nations begin with Philistia (four of the five traditional Philistine cities — Gath is absent, possibly already destroyed). The wordplays: Gaza (<em>azah</em>) / deserted (<em>azuvah</em>); Ekron (<em>eqron</em>) / uprooted (<em>te'aqer</em>). Ashdod's people driven out at noon — in the ancient Near East, noon was the time of military assault when defenders expected rest; the assault at noon signals the completeness and surprise of the judgment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Woe to you inhabitants of the seacoast, the nation of the Cherethites! The word of YHWH is against you, O Canaan, land of the Philistines; and I will destroy you until no inhabitant is left.' The Cherethites were likely Cretans (their name connects to Crete), part of the Sea Peoples who settled the Philistine coast in the 12th century BCE. David's personal guard included Cherethites and Pelethites (2 Sam 8:18; 20:7) — another group of Sea Peoples. The identification of Philistia as Canaanite territory situates its judgment within the broader Deuteronomic framework of Canaanite displacement.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'And you, O seacoast, shall be pastures, with meadows for shepherds and folds for flocks.' The reversal of the Philistine coast: from fortified coastal cities and prosperous trade to open shepherd country. The transformation from urban civilization to pastoral wilderness is a standard judgment image (cf. Isa 32:14; Mic 3:12), but here it also implies depopulation — the shepherds who will use the land are unspecified, possibly Israelites reclaiming territory (v. 7).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The seacoast shall become the possession of the remnant of the house of Judah, on which they shall graze, and in the houses of Ashkelon they shall lie down at evening. For YHWH their God will be mindful of them and restore their fortunes.' The remnant (<em>she'erit beit Yehudah</em>) receives the Philistine coast as an inheritance — the restoration of territory promised in the Abrahamic covenant and partially realized in David's kingdom. 'YHWH will be mindful of them' (<em>yifqedem YHWH Eloheihem</em>) — the verb <em>paqad</em> (visit/attend to) is the covenant attention language of the Exodus (Exod 3:16; 4:31). Restoration follows judgment.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'I have heard the taunts of Moab and the revilings of the Ammonites, how they have taunted my people and made boasts against their territory.' The oracle turns east to Transjordan: Moab and Ammon (both descended from Lot — Gen 19:37-38). Their specific sin is taunting Israel during its period of vulnerability — the standard cruelty of neighbors who mock rather than help when a nation is under divine judgment. The same charge is leveled in Obadiah against Edom; Ezekiel 25 against Moab and Edom; Ps 137:7 against Edom at Jerusalem's fall.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Therefore, as I live, declares YHWH of hosts, the God of Israel, Moab shall become like Sodom, and the Ammonites like Gomorrah, a land possessed by nettles and salt pits and a waste forever. The remnant of my people shall plunder them, and the survivors of my nation shall possess them.' Moab and Ammon's judgment is Sodom and Gomorrah — the cities of the plain that included the ancestors of Moab and Ammon in their destruction (Gen 18-19). The irony: the nations descended from Lot, who escaped Sodom's destruction, receive Sodom's judgment. Salt and nettles on their land — the anti-agricultural curse of desolation (Deut 29:23; Jer 17:6).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'This shall be their lot in return for their pride, because they taunted and boasted against the people of YHWH of hosts.' The cause of Moab and Ammon's judgment is stated precisely: pride (<em>ga'avah</em>) and taunting (<em>cherfutam... veyitgadelu</em>). The same pride that led to Nineveh's fall (Nah 2:3; 3:5) and Edom's (Obad 3) is the sin of all nations who exalt themselves against YHWH's covenant people. The connection between pride and judgment is a major prophetic theme — it is YHWH's own honor (<em>ga'on</em>) that is at stake when nations mock his people.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'YHWH will be awesome against them; for he will famish all the gods of the earth, and to him shall bow down, each in its place, all the lands of the nations.' The eschatological dimension: all gods of the earth are starved of their worship (<em>yarazzeh</em>, famish/shrivel) when the nations who served them are judged. The universal bow-down to YHWH from every place echoes Isa 45:23 (quoted in Phil 2:10-11). This verse extends the Transjordanian oracle into a vision of universal divine sovereignty — the judgment of particular nations is the mechanism through which universal acknowledgment of YHWH is secured.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'You also, O Cushites, shall be slain by my sword.' The brief oracle against Cush (Nubia/Ethiopia) — the southernmost nation. The four-direction structure of the foreign-nation oracles (Philistia=west, Moab/Ammon=east, Cush=south, Assyria=north) represents the four compass points of ancient Near Eastern geography, making the judgment universal in scope. Cush's mention may also glance at the Cushite dynasty that ruled Egypt in the 25th dynasty (ca. 747-656 BCE) — major players in Judah's geopolitical environment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'And he will stretch out his hand against the north and destroy Assyria, and he will make Nineveh a desolation, a dry waste like the desert.' The northern oracle caps the four-direction sequence with the most dramatic judgment: Nineveh, the capital of the Assyrian empire that dominated the ancient Near East. Written while Assyria still controlled the ancient world (the empire collapsed in 612 BCE), this oracle is either remarkable predictive prophecy or was placed here in light of subsequent events. The dry waste and desert (<em>tziyah kemidbar</em>) anticipate Nahum's detailed description of Nineveh's fall.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Herds shall lie down in her midst, all kinds of beasts; even the owl and the hedgehog shall lodge in her capitals; a voice shall hoot in the window; devastation shall be on the threshold; for her cedar work shall be laid bare.' The desolated city repopulated by animals — the great reversal of urban civilization. Owls, hedgehogs, and various beasts (the exact species are uncertain in translation) inhabit what had been Nineveh's royal palace. The cedar work exposed (<em>arzah ye'arah</em>) — the imported Lebanese cedar that decorated Assyrian palaces, now rotting in the open air. Archaeological evidence confirms the thorough desolation of Nineveh after 612 BCE.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'This is the exultant city that lived securely, that said in her heart, I am, and there is no one else. What a desolation she has become, a lair for wild animals! Everyone who passes by her hisses and shakes his fist.' The I am, and there is no one else (<em>ani ve'afsi od</em>) is the supreme claim to divine uniqueness — used by YHWH himself in Isa 45:5-6, 18, 22; 46:9. Nineveh's arrogation of divine self-sufficiency is the deepest form of human pride. The hissing of passersby (<em>yishriq</em>) was the standard gesture of contempt and horror at a destroyed city (1 Kgs 9:8; Jer 19:8; 49:17; Lam 2:15). What was the world's greatest city is now a spectacle of ruin.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>'Woe to her who is rebellious and defiled, the oppressing city!' The final chapter returns from the foreign nations to Jerusalem itself — the woe oracle now aimed at Jerusalem, identified by its characteristics: rebellious (<em>moreh</em>, refusing instruction), defiled (<em>nig'alah</em>, polluted/unclean), and oppressing (<em>hayonah</em>, literally the dove, but used here in the sense of one who presses/oppresses). The same city that could have been the model of covenant justice is condemned in the same terms as the foreign nations.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'She listens to no voice; she accepts no correction. She does not trust in YHWH; she does not draw near to her God.' Four-fold indictment of Jerusalem's spiritual failure: no listening (<em>lo shame'ah beqol</em>), no accepting correction (<em>lo liqchah musar</em>), no trust in YHWH (<em>lo vatcha baYHWH</em>), no drawing near to God (<em>lo qarevah el-Eloheiha</em>). The four failures correspond to the four means of relationship with YHWH: hearing Torah, receiving prophetic reproof, faith, and worship. Jerusalem has failed in all four dimensions simultaneously.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Her officials within her are roaring lions; her judges are evening wolves that leave nothing till the morning.' The leadership metaphors: officials as lions (<em>aryayot sho'agim</em>, roaring), judges as evening wolves (<em>ze'evei erev</em>). Evening wolves were those most dangerous at dusk — when they prowled for prey before retiring at dawn. By dawn they had consumed everything. The officials and judges who were appointed to protect the people consume them instead. The predatory leadership imagery pervades the prophets (Mic 3:1-3; Ezek 22:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Her prophets are fickle, treacherous men; her priests have profaned what is holy; they have done violence to the law.' The second pair of corrupt offices: prophets (<em>nevi'iha pach'azim anshei begadot</em>, frivolous/reckless treacherous men) and priests (<em>kohaneiha chilelu qodesh chomsu Torah</em>, who profane the holy and do violence to Torah). The priests' role was to maintain the boundaries between holy and common, clean and unclean (Lev 10:10; Ezek 44:23); they have blurred or abolished those boundaries. Doing violence to Torah (<em>chomsu Torah</em>) means treating the divine instruction as an obstacle to be overcome rather than a boundary to be respected.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'YHWH within her is righteous; he does no injustice; every morning he shows forth his justice; each dawn he does not fail; but the unjust knows no shame.' The contrast with the corrupt leaders: YHWH himself, who dwells within Jerusalem (unlike the leaders who prey on it), is consistently righteous — every morning, at each dawn, his justice appears. The dawn (<em>laboqer... boqer</em>) setting may be the city gate where legal decisions were rendered (Ruth 4:1-2; Amos 5:15). But the unjust (<em>avval</em>) know no shame — the consistent presence of divine righteousness has not moved them to change.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'I have cut off nations; their battlements are in ruins; I have laid waste their streets so that no one walks in them; their cities have been made desolate, without a man, without an inhabitant.' YHWH speaks: the destruction of other nations was a lesson for Jerusalem, but Jerusalem did not learn it. The devastated cities — presumably the nations judged in ch. 2 — serve as visual object lessons of divine power. If YHWH cut off Philistia, Moab, Ammon, Cush, and Assyria, Jerusalem should have understood its own vulnerability. Instead: v. 7.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'I said, Surely you will fear me; you will accept correction. Then your dwelling would not be cut off according to all that I have appointed against you. But all the more they were eager to make all their deeds corrupt.' The divine expectation voiced: Jerusalem should have seen the destruction of the nations and feared. The phrase 'all that I have appointed against you' (<em>kol asher paqadeti aleiha</em>) suggests that even the specific judgments against other nations were designed as warnings to Jerusalem. Instead (<em>achen hishkimu hishchitu kol alilotam</em>) — they rose early to corrupt all their deeds. Early rising in Hebrew idiom signals eager, deliberate action (cf. Jer 7:13; 11:7; 25:3 — YHWH's persistent speaking; here human eagerness for corruption).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Therefore wait for me, declares YHWH, for the day when I rise up to seize the prey. For my decision is to gather nations, to assemble kingdoms, to pour out upon them my indignation, all my burning anger; for in the fire of my jealousy all the earth shall be consumed.' The pivot from accusation to eschatological promise: the Day of YHWH against the nations is simultaneously the day of Israel's vindication. YHWH rises up as a witness (<em>laed</em>) or as one seizing prey (<em>letor</em> — the verb used of a bird of prey swooping). The universal gathering of nations for judgment in YHWH's jealousy-fire anticipates Joel 3's valley of judgment and Rev 20's great white throne.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'For at that time I will change the speech of the peoples to a pure speech, that all of them may call upon the name of YHWH and serve him with one accord.' The restoration oracle that follows judgment: the reversal of Babel. At Babel, YHWH confused the speech of the nations (Gen 11:7-9); at the eschatological restoration, YHWH gives the nations a pure lip (<em>safah verurah</em>) — unified language to call on his name. The universal calling on YHWH's name (<em>liqro kulam beshem YHWH</em>) echoes Joel 2:32 (Acts 2:21; Rom 10:13). The unity of worship across all peoples serving YHWH shoulder to shoulder (<em>shechem echad</em>, one shoulder/accord) is the end of Babel's division.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'From beyond the rivers of Cush my worshipers, the daughter of my dispersed ones, shall bring my offering.' The furthest reaches of the known world — beyond Cush (the rivers of Cush = Nile tributaries in Nubia, the southernmost boundary of the known world) — will bring offerings to YHWH. The dispersed ones (<em>bat putzai</em>) are YHWH's scattered people, gathered from exile. The offering they bring is themselves — the ingathering of exiles is itself the sacrifice that YHWH receives.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'On that day you shall not be put to shame because of the deeds by which you have rebelled against me; for then I will remove from your midst your proudly exultant ones, and you shall no longer be haughty in my holy mountain.' The shame of the exile removed. The specific condition for restored dignity: the removal of the proudly exultant ones (<em>alyzei ga'avatech</em>, those exulting in your pride) from the midst of Jerusalem. The pride that caused the fall is surgically removed; what remains is a humble community that does not boast on YHWH's holy mountain.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'But I will leave in your midst a people humble and lowly. They shall seek refuge in the name of YHWH.' The remnant (<em>she'erit</em>) theology reaches its clearest expression: the remnant is defined not by ethnic purity or national affiliation but by character — humble (<em>ani vedalh</em>, poor and afflicted) and those who seek refuge in YHWH's name. This is the Beatitude pattern before the Beatitudes: the poor in spirit who inherit the kingdom (Matt 5:3). The name of YHWH is the refuge, not the walls of Jerusalem or the political alliances that the princes pursued.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'The remnant of Israel; they shall do no injustice and speak no lies, nor shall there be found in their mouth a deceitful tongue. For they shall graze and lie down, and none shall make them afraid.' The remnant's character: no injustice, no lies, no deceit — the exact vices of the oppressing city described in 3:1-4. The restoration reverses the corruption. The pastoral image of lying down in safety (none to make them afraid) directly echoes Micah 4:4 (every man under his vine and fig tree, none to make them afraid) and Ezek 34:28 (the good shepherd's flock at rest). The covenant blessings of Lev 26:6 and Deut 28 are fulfilled.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Sing aloud, O daughter of Zion; shout, O Israel! Rejoice and exult with all your heart, O daughter of Jerusalem!' The sudden turn to celebration is one of the most dramatic pivots in the entire prophetic corpus. After fifteen verses of cosmic wrath (ch. 1) and the detailed judgment of nations and Jerusalem (ch. 2-3:1-13), the prophet breaks into an imperative of joy. Four verbs of celebration in two verses: sing, shout, rejoice, exult. The daughter of Zion is addressed as the one who will receive the restored divine presence.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'YHWH has taken away the judgments against you; he has cleared away your enemies. The King of Israel, YHWH, is in your midst; you shall never again fear evil.' The three gifts of restoration: removal of judgments (<em>hitir mishpatayich</em>), clearing of enemies (<em>pinna oyevaich</em>), and the divine King's presence (<em>melech Yisrael YHWH bekerevech</em>). YHWH as King of Israel in the midst of his people is the fulfillment of the Sinai covenant's central promise (Lev 26:11-12; Exod 29:45-46). 'You shall never again fear evil' — the exact reversal of the Day of YHWH's terror announced in ch. 1.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'On that day it shall be said to Jerusalem: Fear not, O Zion; let not your hands grow weak.' The encouragement formula 'Fear not' (<em>al tiri</em>) is the angel's greeting to those who receive divine appearances (Gen 15:1; 26:24; Dan 10:12; Luke 1:13, 30; 2:10). Weak hands (<em>al yirpu yadayich</em>, do not let your hands go slack) is the image of discouragement and helplessness (2 Sam 4:1; Isa 35:3; Heb 12:12). The restoration makes Jerusalem capable of action — her hands are strengthened.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'YHWH your God is in your midst, a mighty one who will save; he will rejoice over you with gladness; he will quiet you by his love; he will exult over you with loud singing.' One of the most remarkable verses in the OT: YHWH himself sings over his people. The divine warrior (<em>gibbor yoshi'a</em>, mighty one who saves) is simultaneously the singer. YHWH rejoices (<em>yasis</em>) and exults (<em>yagil</em>) — the same verbs used of Israel's commanded rejoicing in v. 14, now attributed to YHWH himself. The quieting in love (<em>yacharish be'ahavato</em>) — the silence of deep contentment and satisfaction. The image of YHWH singing over restored Jerusalem is without parallel in the prophetic corpus.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'I will gather those of you who mourn for the festival, so that you will no longer suffer reproach.' The gathering of those who mourned for the festivals (<em>nugei mo'ed asafti mimcha hayu</em>) — those exiled who could not attend Jerusalem's pilgrimage festivals and mourned their absence. The Psalms of Ascent (Pss 120-134) express this longing. The reproach (<em>cherpa</em>) of exile — the shame of deportation, the mockery of enemies — is removed in the gathering.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Behold, at that time I will deal with all your oppressors. And I will save the lame and gather the outcast, and I will change their shame into praise and renown in all the earth.' The lame (<em>hatzoleat</em>) and the outcast (<em>hanidachah</em>) — those on the margins of society who were excluded from full participation in communal life — are specifically gathered. The same categories appear in Micah 4:6-7: YHWH will gather the lame and the driven away. The shame-to-praise reversal is the eschatological transformation of status: those who were last become known throughout all the earth.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'At that time I will bring you in, at the time when I gather you together; for I will make you renowned and praised among all the peoples of the earth, when I restore your fortunes before your eyes, says YHWH.' The final verse of Zephaniah closes with the promise that spans the entire book: from the universal judgment of ch. 1 to the universal restoration of ch. 3. The restoration of fortunes (<em>beshuvi et shevuteichem</em>) is a standard post-exilic phrase for the reversal of exile (Deut 30:3; Jer 30:3; Joel 4:1; Amos 9:14). The final clause — 'before your eyes, says YHWH' — grounds the promise in the immediacy of divine speech addressed to the very people who will see it fulfilled.</p>"
  }
}

